reviews.review_text: Very Nice Sound Can't be sure about the entire show--skipped to the second set--but the sound is excellent. And the playing is very delicate, mellow.  I like mellow shows sometimes, and if you do too, this one is worth it.

Time Flies Wow, what a show. Nobody weighing in on this one since 2008? First, a Betty board. Second, check out the Franklin's. You can't walk up to the song any slower and more sincerely. They kind of introduce you to the song, because the song indeed exists in a world of its own. Third, Betty board.

FYI Phil gives the update on the TKO by Muhammad Ali from the Ali/Shaver fight after Half-Step.  

Seattle and Portland shows are seemingly always hot, year after year.  This one  from late 1977 is no exception.

Great show, great era This is one of those under the radar shows that exemplify exactly how amazing the Grateful Dead were.  Late 77, Jerry's voice never sounded so good.  The quality on this is first rate, the separation of the guitars, Bobby comes through beautifully.  The boys are taking their time and enjoying themselves.  The last 30 minutes are priceless, even when Jerry screws up Stella Blue he still turns it into a masterpiece, and Uncle Johns doesn't get any better.  Worth the listen!

Noticed Stiff Rhythm section Unfortunately, from the moment I started the first set it was pretty obvious and painful how the drummers were completely lacking in fluidity... I jumped ahead to Sugaree where Jerry was trying to move them off "the one" but it didn't take! such is GOGD... sometimes!
The end of the first set and beginning of the second did not move me to listen further when there are so many other excellent choices!
